msDesc.head: Alexander of Tralles, Practica, and other medical texts

summary.seg: Most of this 13th-century manuscript comprises a copy of the Latin translation of the Greek medical text, Theraupetica, which was written by Alexander of Tralles perhaps around the second quarter or middle of the 6th century. The identity of the translator or translators is not known, nor the period in which it was produced, though it must have been before the turn of the 8th-9th century, the date of the earliest surviving manuscript copy (now Paris, Bibliotheque nationale de France, MS lat. 9332). It has been suggested that the translation was made shortly after the composition of the Greek original, in Ravenna or Rome, which were important centres in the production of medical literature. As D.R. Langslow (2006) has pointed out, firmer conclusions could be drawn if it were possible to establish 'close linguistic links' between the Latin version of the Theraupetica and the Latin translation of Oribasius's medical works, which is now widely accepted to have been produced in Ravenna - but further work remains to be done.

Alexander's medical analysis and advice is organised according to human body, in head-to-toe order. The Latin text is divided into three sections, dealing first with ailments of the head, from hair-loss to issues with the face and teeth, then problems of the lungs, coughing and diseases of the liver and gout, and finally fevers in general. The two versions are broadly similar and of similar length overall, however there are some differences between the Greek original and the Latin translation, arising from both the addition of new material and the omission of some parts of the Greek text.

Tuija Ainonen
Project Cataloguer
Cambridge University Library

foliation.note: Foliated in red crayon in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the upper outer corner of each recto.

collation.p:
Quires of mostly eight leaves arranged as follows:
Quires 1-88 (ff. 4-67)
Quire 910 (ff. 68-77)
Quire 108 (ff. 78-85)
Quire 1110-1 (4th leaf (after f. 88) cancelled; ff. 86-94)

signatures.p: Quires are numbered in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the lower outer corner of the first recto of each quire.

supportDesc.condition: Minor rodent damage to the tail edge of the quires.

binding.p: 19th century binding. Fully bound in calf over paste- or mill- boards with matching decoration in blind to left and right covers. Covers are each decorated with two concentric triple-fillet frames, the outer frame set at the perimeter of the boards, and the inner frame inset by 20 mm. Each corner of the inner frame is joined to the nearest corner of the outer frame with a triple fillet. Decorative arcade-and-fleur-de-lis roll applied in blind to head, fore, and tail edges of the covers.

Five raised bands on the spine. Spine is capped at head and tail by the cover material and no head or tail bands are visible. Spine compartments are decorated along their upper and lower perimeters with a triple fillet. Title label applied in black leather with the title ALEX. TRALLIANI ET 3. ALII TRACTATUS tooled in gold. Two small printed paper labels affixed to spine 729 and 400.
Dimensions: 250 x 180 x 32 mm (L x W x D)

Folio 1, a fragment, was probably once used as a pastedown in an older binding, although it seems to have been displaced from its earlier codicological position. There are four sets of three sewing holes along the present inner edge of f. 1, two small semi-rectangular patches of abrasion and damage along its outer edge, and there is significant adhesive residue on f. 1v; the position and location of these features suggests that the leaf was once used as the right pastedown in an earlier binding, or perhaps as the lining for a spine.

history.acquisition: At Gonville and Caius College by 1600, when it was recorded as no. 99 in the Ecloga Oxonio-Cantabrigiensis by Thomas James (1600); this designation was recorded in ink in the upper margin of f. 4v.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on M. R. James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, 2 vols. (Cambridge, 1907-1908) vol. 2, pp. 464-65.

collation.p:
This Part is mostly comprised of quires of eight leaves, with two quires of ten leaves. The stub after f. 88 is from a cancelled leaf, comparison of the text with that found in Oxford, Bodleian Library, MS Digby 79 revealing no gap between ff. 88v and 89r.
Quires 1-88 (ff. 4-67)
Quire 910 (ff. 68-77)
Quire 108 (ff. 78-85)
Quire 1110-1 (4th leaf (after f. 88) cancelled; ff. 86-94)

signatures.p: No leaf signatures particular to this Part.
Quires are numbered in ink in Roman majuscules in the centre of the lower margin of the last verso of Quires 1-7: ff. 11v, 19v, 27v, 35v, 43v, 51v, and 59v.

catchwords.seg: No catchwords particular to this Part.

supportDesc.condition: Folio 94 reduced, now c. 175 x 100 mm.

layoutDesc.layout:
Written space 180-185 125-135
Ruled in leadpoint frame and lines, ruling often faint with single vertical bounding lines extending the full height of the page, and the first, second, thirty-sixth and thirty-seventh horizontal lines extending the full width of the page. Mainly in single columns, except for ff. 4v-5r (chapter list) and 84r-93v, which have two columns. Typical leaves have 36-37 lines to the page, written above top line. Pricked in the outer margins.

decoNote.p: Seven- to ten-line initials in gold, red, green and blue with foliate motifs at the beginning of each text (ff. 5v, 35r, 76r, 84r, 90v).

Two- to four-line 'arabesque' and coloured initials in alternating red, green, yellow and blue until f. 54v, after that in alternating red and green; some simple, some decorated with fronds and dots in red, green and yellow.
Chapter headings and section divisions in red.

binding.p: Potential traces of former binding on f. 4r: Perforation in the four corners of the parchment, and a central hole that shows signs of oxidisation.
